<p class="lead"><strong>Justification and alignment refer to how the text is positioned in the
document in relation to the margins of the document.</strong></p class="lead">

<p>The usual default setting for word processors is to justify or align to the
left side of the document. This means when you start typing, the line of text
begins at the left and as you type, the words go from left to right, with the
text wrapping in this same way. When you press enter to start a new paragraph
or section, the cursor starts a new line of text on the left side of the
document, aligned with the left margin.</p>

<p>However, you do have options in how the text of the document will align.
There is both horizontal alignment (how text is positioned relative to the left
and right margins) and vertical alignment (how text is positioned relative to
the top and bottom margins).</p>

<p>Let's learn about the options and effects.</p>



<div class="row">
<div class="twelve columns">
<h4>Horizontal alignment</h4>

<p>Horizontal alignment refers to how text is positioned in relation to the
left and right margins of a document. There are four settings buttons in the
toolbar you can choose from:</p>

<ul class="disc">

    <li><strong>Align Left</strong> - each the line of text is positioned evenly with the left margin</li>

    <li><strong>Center</strong> - each line of text is centered between the left and right margins</li>

    <li><strong>Align Right</strong> - each line of text is positioned evenly with the right margin</li>

    <li><strong>Justify</strong> - each line of text is centered between the left and right margins evenly</p>

<p>The images below are examples of the horizontal alignment setting buttons
you are likely to find in the toolbar at the top of an open document. The icon
on the button shows you the effect on the text of each setting.</p>

